<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Banks Shun Loans to Real Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Despite having a higher
monetary base than the month before, Thailand's commercial banks
continued to refrain from providing new loans to the real economic
sector in July, making the Bank of Thailand's attempts to increase
liquidity in the sector unsuccessful, a central bank report
available Saturday said.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that the country's monetary base at the end
of July was 448.1 billion baht (11.2 billion U.S. dollars), a 0.05
percent increase from a month ago, due to a rise in deposits by
financial institutions with the central bank.
</P>
<P>
However, total credit of banks fell 0.0043 percent to 4.63
trillion baht (115.7 billion dollars) during the same period.
</P>
<P>
The figures indicated that liquidity problems in the domestic
money market had eased, as evidenced by several banks' move to cut
deposit and lending rates.
</P>
<P>
Deposit rates currently range between 8 and 9 percent, while
interest spreads range from between 5 and 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that banks were using the gain from the
widening spread to subsidize their non-performing loans (NPLs),
and some analysts had suspected that the banks were using the new
money for overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
As the report stated, the central banks is still facing the
challenging task of encouraging commercial banks to extend new
loans to the real sector, given that banks are reluctant to incur
the higher risks of such extensions at the moment for fear that
their NPLs will escalate sharply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
