<HEADLINE> Communists Reiterate Call for Yeltsin's Ouster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Communist Party
Saturday planned a nationwide campaign for October 7 to demand the
ouster of President Boris Yeltsin, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov said a meeting of the
Communist Party central committee decided that the October
campaign would also call for an end to the current government
policy and the establishment of a new "government of national
interests."
</P>
<P>
The meeting instructed Communist lawmakers to seek changes to
the constitution and to the government law so that the government
"does not depend on Mr. Yeltsin's mood" and does not leave office
without making a report to the legislature, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party is the largest faction in the State Duma,
or lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov said the Communists' attitude towards the government
of Yevgeny Primakov would depend on its program and "concrete
steps."
</P>
<P>
He said the left-wing opposition planned to demand that the
Primakov cabinet support Russian manufacturers, set an official
subsistence minimum and take every measure to stabilize the
situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The committee also elected 180 delegates for a congress of the
Union of Communist Parties-Communist Party of the Soviet Union, an
association of Communist parties in former Soviet republics,
Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
