<HEADLINE> Thailand Censors International Film Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 19 (Xinhua) -- All film entries for
Thailand's first international film festival were subject to
censorship before being shown, festival organizers said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A censorship board has been set up to view all film entries to
ensure that they meet the country's strict censorship law, said
the organizers.
</P>
<P>
At least one entry, Bugis Street, by Singaporean director
Yonfan, has already officially been banned from the festival that
began on Friday. Others were likely to be withdrawn for failing to
conform with the censorship law.
</P>
<P>
Bugis Street features transvestites who populated Singapore's
notorious red-light district in 1960. The censorship board deemed
it pornographic.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Film Festival was scheduled to screen 50 features
and 80 short films and documentaries from 18 countries between
September 18-26. It intended to highlight independent films
produced by dedicated film makers on shoe-string budgets,
organizer Brian Bennet said.
</P>
<P>
The film circles in Thailand want to turn Bangkok into a film
festival hub. But film critics said this dream would face real
problems because of the censorship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
