<HEADLINE> Five Iranians Released by Taliban Arrive in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Five Iranians arrived here
Saturday night by a special plane from the southern Afghan city of
Kandahar.
 The five Iranians were released Friday by the Afghan Taliban
militia as "a goodwill gesture" to the Iranian side. The Taliban
had already released five Iranians on September 3.
Senior Taliban official Maulvi Rehmatullah told reporters
Saturday upon his arrival that "it is Iran's turn to take
practical steps to reduce the current tension" between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
"We demand that Iran should remove its troops from the
Afghan-Iran border. We don't want war with Iran. We don't want
second war with any country," he said.
He also said the killing of Iranian diplomats in Mazar-i-Sharif
were done by "renegades."
It is a problem deliberately created by some people for the
Taliban, he added.
Rehmatullah said that the Taliban authorities have set up a
commission to investigate the incident and will apprehend and
arrest the "culprits." 
</P>
</TEXT>
