<HEADLINE> 2 Killed, 30 Injured in Bus Accident in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Two people were killed and 30
others were injured Saturday in a bus accident near the Greek town
of Krioneri, Attica province.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred when a Halkida-Athens inter-city bus fell
in a 10-meter-deep ravine.
</P>
<P>
Road accidents kill about 3,000 people and injure some 30,000
in Greece per year with drunk drive and high speed being blamed
for most of the accidents.
</P>
<P>
To reduce the number of car accidents, Greek traffic police
have reportedly made substantial inroads in strictly carrying out
alcohol breathalyser tests and imposing stiff penalties introduced
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Traffic police have tested 202,000 drivers nationwide from
August 1997 to August 1998, while a total of 1,707 cars have been
impounded just to be given back after court hearings. Out of the
202,000 drivers tested, traffic police found 14,000 individuals
over the limit (0.5 parts per thousand).
</P>
<P>
In Attica alone, of 76,000 breathalysers tests carried out over
the last year, 6,704 drivers were found to have high levels of
alcohol in their blood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
