<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Militia Ready to Withdraw Under Certain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Pro-Israeli South Lebanon
Army (SLA) chief Antoine Lahd said Saturday that his forces are
ready to withdraw from their controlled town Jezzine in southern
Lebanon provided the government meets its demands.
</P>
<P>
He told foreign news agencies here that the demands are that
the government agrees to send its troops to Jezzine and
maintain its security, and promises not to allow other military
groups to enter the area.
</P>
<P>
Lahd's comments came one day after his militia withdrew from a
SLA major post at Toumat Niha, east of Jezzine.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's independent Central News Agency quoted security
sources as saying that the SLA's redeployment represented the
first step of its withdrawal plan from Jezzine.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the SLA will implement its plan on
stages.
</P>
<P>
The SLA militia has been policing Jezzine and helping Israeli
forces patrol its security zone in south Lebanon since it was
established in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the self-declared security zone to allegedly
protect its north from cross-border attack by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Lahd said that the latest security measures he adopted in
Jezzine are not aimed at annexing the area to the "security zone,"
but for the area's security.
</P>
<P>
On September 10, Lahd announced that all residents of Jezzine
would have to apply for special travel permits 48 hours prior to
leaving or returning the area.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the measures were taken because of the rising
number of Hezbollah bombing attacks launched inside the district,
leading to heavy casualties of residents and SLA members.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah (Party of God) is spearheading a
guerrilla war trying to oust 1,000 Israeli troops and SLA
militiamen out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
