<HEADLINE> Russia Denies Plan to Monopolize Tobacco Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government
Saturday denied media reports that it plans to monopolize the
production and sales of tobacco and nationalize the entire tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
The government is only considering measures to "put in order"
the manufacture and especially imports of tobacco products, Anton
Surikov, spokesman for First Deputy Prime Minister Yuri Maslyukov,
said.
</P>
<P>
He said between 50 billion and 60 billion cigarettes were
smuggled into Russia last year, costing the government more than 1
billion U.S. dollars, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Surikov said the government was also looking at proposals to
simplify licensing tobacco imports, set up a wholesale tobacco
network and ban new privileged terms for tobacco imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
