<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM: Government Not to Use Criminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz said here Saturday that no government establishment,
including the intelligence service, should use criminals in their
operations.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz's words came when allegations that some government
officials kept close relations with members of mafias were growing
louder.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz admitted that the National Intelligence Agency (MIT) had
used criminals "in the past" in its operations.
</P>
<P>
No major problems in Turkey could be solved unless the links
between crime gangs, state bureaucracy and politics were uprooted,
said Yilmaz.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister added that no government agency should use
any individual wanted in the country or sentenced by the courts.
</P>
<P>
He said use of criminals for any purpose by the state could not
reconcile with his understanding of state and government.
</P>
<P>
A special unit was set up at the Police Department to pursue
the gangs, said Yilmaz, adding that coordination was established
between the police and the MIT so that the two state agencies
could work more effectively against gangs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prime minister disclosed that 13.634 tonnes of
drugs have been seized since his government came to power in June
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's organized crimes have been on rise in recent years,
causing serious social trouble. 
</P>
</TEXT>
