<HEADLINE> Turkish President Urges Media to Fight Slander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel on Saturday urged editors of the news organizations around
the world to protect individual privacy and fight slander.
</P>
<P>
Demirel made the remarks at the opening speech of the World
Conference and General Assembly of the World Association of Press
Councils meeting in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey,
the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He asked newsmen to fight "smear, defamation and slander that
might appear in the media." "The media has a natural legitimacy to
act and speak in the name of society as a whole," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that "this is the reason why it must tell the truth
without fear or favor, without taking sides with any interest
group. It must be clean, dignified and trustworthy while
discharging its enormous civil tasks."
</P>
<P>
About 230 editors and experts on press law from more than 30
countries are participating in the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
