<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JEDDAH -- Chief of Islamic Bank for Development (IBD) Ahmed
Mohammed Ali said the training course on trade policies is part of
the effort of the standing committee for economic cooperation and
trade exchanges, an affiliate of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the three-week course, Ali
said the aim of the course is to coordinate the efforts of the
member countries in the face of the challenges posed by the trade
globalization and the new world trade order.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The visit of the Armenian businessman delegation,
headed by Prime Minister Armen Darbinyan, to Lebanon helped the
businessmen of the two countries define the available investment
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The visit also encouraged setting up of joint ventures and and
enhancing exports as well as the exchange of commodities and
services between the two countries, Al-Hayat daily reported.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Arab Petroleum Investment Co. (APICO) signed an
agreement with the Finnish Nesti Co., the Italian Icofuel and the
Saudi Algin.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement the four firms will launch the National
Corporation for Fuel Improvement "Tahsin" (improvement) with a
capital of 500 million riyals (over 133 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
APICO said that the project aims to set up the world's largest
plant for fuel improvement in Yanbo'e city, Saudi Arabia. Its
capacity will hit 90,000 tonnes annually. It will start production
in early 2001.
</P>
<P>
The Algin will have a stake of 25 to 30 percent of the project,
the Icofuel 15 percent, APICO 10 percent and the remaining will be
taken by a number of Saudi and Gulf firms.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Service related to the Internet is booming in Jordan,
which has seven ISP (Internet service provider) companies and
around 70 Internet cafes for its 4.6 million people.
</P>
<P>
The ISP companies have over 30,000 customers and each Internet
cafe has at least 10 regular visitors, it added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan legalized the Internet use in its territory in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
