<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon, Kuwait Sign Trade Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon and Kuwait Saturday
singed a trade agreement to remove customs duties on industrial
products, paving the way for the establishment of a free trade
zone between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Kuwaiti Minister of Commerce and Industry Abdel Aziz
al-Dekheel and his Lebanese counterpart Yassin Jaber signed the
agreement, the independent Central News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two countries will reduce customs
taxes on industrial products by 25 percent annually, starting
from January 1, 1999, until ultimately they become customs-free.
</P>
<P>
Jaber said after the signing ceremony that this is an
important step on the road toward liberating Arab economy and
establishing a free Arab trade zone.
</P>
<P>
For his part, the Kuwaiti minister who arrived here Friday to
open the first Kuwaiti products exhibition, welcomed the pact,
hoping it would provide an easy access for his country's
industrial products to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Lebanon signed a similar pact with Egypt and
an agreement to remove customs taxes on agricultural products with
its neighbor Syria.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, which is recovering from its 1975-1990 civil war, is
attempting to restore its one-time reputation as a commercial
center in the region by promoting its free trade policy.
</P>
<P>
During the fair, Kuwaiti companies complained that they had
difficulties selling their products in Lebanon because of the
high customs rates.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon is imposing a 22 percent customs duty on industrial
products while in Kuwait it is 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries in 1997 stood at 77 million
U.S. dollars, of which 60 million dollars were Lebanese exports
to Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
