<HEADLINE> African Police Urged to Fight Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 19 (Xinhua) -- A Tanzanian official
has called on police forces of African countries to arm
themselves with necessary skills and join hands in fighting drug
traffickers, according to a press release reaching here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Time has gone when one country was able to combat this type
of crime alone, " Professor Philemon Sarungi, the Kilimanjaro
Regional Commissioner, said Friday in Tanzania's northern town of
Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Closing a five-day training seminar for drug law enforcement
personnel from eastern and southern African countries, Sarungi
pointed out that lack of properly trained law enforcement
officers diminished the chances of success.
</P>
<P>
He urged 30 drug personnel who attended the training course to
further improve efficiency in controling illicit drug business.
</P>
<P>
Sarungi said that close cooperation among police of different
states is not enough, and only skillful personnel have greater
chances of nabbing criminals.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the chairman of the seminar, Tanzania's Director of
Criminal Investigations Adadi Rajabu said: "We see this
particular training as a step forward toward a particular goal --
eradication of drugs trafficking."
</P>
<P>
The seminar came at a time when drug traffickers increasingly
turn Africa into a transit for their business.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was opened by Zanzibar Chief Minister Mohammed
Gharib Bilal Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
