<HEADLINE> 3,900 Zambians Die in Road Accidents During </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The National Crime Foundation
of Zambia disclosed Saturday that 3,901 deaths and 15,140 serious
or permanent injuries were recorded in road accidents throughout
the country from 1994 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the foundations's workshop on the prevention of
crime in Zambia here, chairman of the organization Francis
Musonda said the driving of faulty vehicleso roads and other
factors have been leading to the decrease in the standard of
safety of the roads.
</P>
<P>
Musonda singled out bad driving habits and drunken driving as
the major problems causing major road accidents.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the foundation has shown that awareness
of many road users on safety issues has declined, the Zambian
News Agency quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The one-day workshop was intended to mobilize community
resources, skill, talent and ideas to ensure that the Zambian
roads are safe. 
