<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Says Disarmament Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein's chief negotiator
Martin McGuinness said Saturday he believed the disarmament of
Northern Ireland's paramilitary organizations was possible.
</P>
<P>
However, McGuinness said decommissioning of arms could only
take place with the full implementation of the Northern Ireland
peace agreement on the political future of the province. The
agreement was reached last April by the main political parties in
the province.
</P>
<P>
This included the appointment of members of Sinn Fein, the
political wing of the Irish Republican Army, to seats in the new
Northern Ireland Executive, he said.
</P>
<P>
Terrorist arms are central to the future of the political
process in Northern Ireland. Over the past 30-year conflict, more
than 3,600 people have been killed by either the Protestant or
Catholic extremists.
</P>
<P>
McGuinness, who is Sinn Fein's go-between with the
international decommissioning body and the IRA, said, "Let's
understand that this process of removing the gun from Irish
politics is going to be a very lengthy one and very
problematical."
</P>
<P>
"I think it can be overcome and I think that we can, if all of
us come at this in a very sensible way, deal with the very complex
and sophisticated issues that are in there and they're best dealt
with in the context of removing the causes of conflict," he said.
</P>
<P>
McGuinness indicated that no progress could be made on
decommissioning until all the other terms of the peace agreement
had been met.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein has been facing increased pressure to deliver some
hand-over of IRA weapons. Northern Ireland First Minister David
Trimble, also the leader of the Ulster Unionist Party, has
insisted that Sinn Fein cannot join the new executive until the
IRA gives up its arsenal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
