<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses Turkey of Meddling in its Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Saturday accused
Turkey of interfering in its internal affairs, calling it
"unacceptable" and against the U.N. Charter and international laws
and principles.
</P>
<P>
The charge was made by a spokesman of Iraq's Ministry of
Culture and Information, in response to a statement made by a
Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman to the effect that northern
Iraq suffers from a power vacuum and needs a new administration.
</P>
<P>
"The statement of the Turkish official was a flagrant,
unacceptable interference in Iraq's internal affairs and a clear
violation of all the international laws and conventions," said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has been rendered ineffective in its control over
northern Iraq since the 1991 Gulf War, in which Iraqi troops were
defeated by U.S.-led allied forces. The U.S. and British forces
are imposing a "no-fly" zone there.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman said that Turkey has contributed since 1991
to the power vacuum in northern Iraq through providing military
base for the U.S. and British forces to interfere militarily and
illegally in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that the power vacuum would continue as long as Iraq's
central government was kept away from that part of the country and
that no new or provisional administration would be able to fill
the vacuum.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that Turkey's policy, which he said is hostile to
Iraq and other Arab countries, and its alliance with Israel, have
made it "but a tool of the U.S. strategy for the Middle East."
</P>
<P>
This goes against Turkey's own interests, he said. "What serves
Turkey's interests and stability is to pay attention to relations
with Iraq and the Arabs instead of alliance with the United States
and Israel," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that a final solution of the problem of northern Iraq
lies in the protection of Iraq's territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Turkey and Iraq have been tense since the
Gulf War when Turkey put one of its military bases at the disposal
of the U.S. and British forces for reconnaissance missions over
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkish troops crossed into northern Iraq many times since 1991
under the pretext of chasing rebels of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party, who fight Ankara for an independent Kurdish state
across the border of northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq attacked the incursions as a violation of its sovereignty
and a threat to its security and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
The recent Turkish-Israeli alliance is another source of
tension between Baghdad and Ankara, as Iraq regards it a threat
targeting Iraq and the Arab nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
