<DOCNO> XIE19980920.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Denies Arming Warheads With VX Gas Anew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Iraq reaffirmed Saturday that
it did not arm its warheads with the deadly VX gas.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant General Amer Al-Saadi, an adviser to President
Saddam Hussein, told reporters here Saturday evening that the
samples that the Swiss and French experts had taken and analized
prove the validity of the Iraqi earlier statements.
</P>
<P>
The experts examined samples of more than 40 parts of warheads
under instructions of one of the representatives of the United
National Special Committee (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating
weapons of mass destruction in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Al-Saadi said the experts noticed that the French and Swiss
laboratories found no existence of the VX gas, adding that some
U.S. officials and the U.S. Department of Defense played down the
results of the findings of the Swiss and French laboratories.
</P>
<P>
The VX issue is the major obstacle in the chemical file,
according to Al-Saadi, and the results of the inspections will be
a positive step.
</P>
<P>
As for the recent crisis between Iraq and the UNSCOM, al-Saadi
said dialog was still going on with U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi high-level mission will leave for New York in the next
few days for talks with Annan as part of the consultations between
Annan and some U.N. Security Council members, the Iraqi official
added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the U.N. Security Council took tough action
against Iraq for freezing weapons inspections, suspending periodic
review of sanctions imposed on Iraq in 1990 after it invaded
Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
