<HEADLINE> Congo Accuses Uganda of Occupying Congo Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Congolese Information
Minister Didier Mumengi Saturday accused Ugandan armed men of
taking the northeastern town of Isiro but said they were chased
out by Congolese army later, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
"A small group entered Isiro from Uganda but today we have
confirmation that Isiro is in the hands of Congolese forces,"
Mumengi, spokesman for President Laurent Kabila's government, was
quoted by the report from Kinshasa as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Kabila's senior political aide and cabinet minister,
Pierre-Victor Mpoyo, said Isiro, a strategic town northeast of
the third city Kisangani, had been seized by Ugandan troops.
</P>
<P>
"This is the work of Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni," Mpoyo
said. "The attackers are Ugandans. They know that we don't have
money to buy artillery to confront them."
</P>
<P>
However, Uganda denied the charge and said it had no troops
in Isiro, a town about 350 km west of Uganda's town of Arua and
200 km south of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
"Each time rebels are mentioned, Kinshasa substitutes Uganda
for the rebels," Uganda's Foreign Minister Amama Mbabazi said
in Kampala. "We have not been in Isiro," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Nobody could confirm the situation in the town, which is in
Oriental province as is Kisangani, Congo's third largest city,
taken by ethnic Tutsi rebels earlier.
</P>
<P>
Mpoyo said he expected the inhabitants of Isiro to resist
foreign occupation just as residents of Kinshasa had foiled a
rebel bid to take it in the last week of August.
</P>
<P>
"They took the town by force but how can they hold it without
the people's support? The army will go in, and if the army fails
to expel them the people will expel them."
</P>
<P>
Mpoyo said the Congolese government had already started
distributing arms for a "people's war" that would end in Rwanda.
He accused Kigali of invading to back the rebels who took up arms
to oust Kabila since August 2.
</P>
<P>
Mpoyo said allied troops from Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia who
drove out rebels from the west of Congo (K) were not keen to be
involved in fighting in the east.
</P>
<P>
In Kinshasa Saturday, handicapped people and groups from
Oriental province marched through the city to express support for
Kabila and condemn what they called international indifference on
foreign invasion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
