<HEADLINE> Regional Leaders Seek Peaceful Solution to Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Presidents of Uganda,
Tanzania and Zambia Yoweri Museveni, Benjamin Mkapa and Frederick
Chiluba discussed peaceful solutions to the crisis in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) in Entebbe, Uganda, Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of Zambia and Tanzania arrived Saturday morning
to make a one-day working visit to Uganda, a press release from
the President's Office said.
</P>
<P>
Zambian President Chiluba, who presided over the talks at the
Imperial Botanical Beach Hotel, said the meeting was mainly aimed
at consulting and searching for a solution to the crisis in Congo
(K). He hailed the meeting as a success and an important step
taken to find a real solution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
All three leaders agreed on ending hostilities and
implementing an immediate cease-fire in the war-torn central
African country.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to adopt the proposed modalities which have
been worked out recently in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, and to
overcome any sticking point on the way to peaceful resolution of
the problem in Africa's third largest country.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is committed to ensuring that the peace process
continues, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said more meetings are likely to be held in the near future
to ensure that the process moves forward expeditiously. 
