<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anhui Vows to Score 10 Percent Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 20 (Xinhua) -- East China's Anhui Province
will certainly score a 10 percent economic growth rate despite of
severe floods this summer.
</P>
<P>
Provincial Governor Hui Liangyu made the remark recently in an
exclusive interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The summer floods killed 102 people, damaged 1.3 million ha. of
farmlands, destroyed over 270,000 houses, and affected a total of
15.72 million residents living along the Yangtze and Huaihe rivers.
</P>
<P>
The floods brought direct financial losses valued at 13 billion
yuan including 9.38 billion yuan in the farming sector to the
province, according to Hui, also secretary of the Provincial
Committee of the Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
Thank to the strenuous efforts of local people, no major
breaches have occurred on river dikes, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The governor attributed Anhui's flood-fighting success to the
remarkable achievements in building new homes and anti-flood
facilities built by the province since it was devastated by severe
floods six years ago.
</P>
<P>
Floods could bring about heavy losses as well as huge demands,
Hui said.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, severe floods brought direct financial losses worth
27.5 billion yuan to Anhui, but in the following six years, the
province achieved an average annual growth of 16.6 percent,
ranking among the fastest in all province-level areas in China, he
recalled.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1991 floods, the province carried out a well-planned
reconstruction program for homeless flood victims, he said, adding
the program has saved large tracts of cultivated land. The
rebuilding program won a U.N. prize in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the province has been readied for the summer
floods as leading government officials at all levels had been made
responsible for dangerous sections of river embankments.
</P>
<P>
Anhui's success has drawn nationwide attention. In late
August this year, a high-level conference attended by leaders
from flood-stricken provinces was held in Anhui to study its
flood-fighting and rebuilding experience.
</P>
<P>
The provincial leader expressed the hope that the floods could
serve as cohesiveness for local people to work harder in economic
fields.
</P>
<P>
Anhui is still among the underdeveloped areas in the country
but aims high, Hui said.
</P>
<P>
The province is now no longer an agricultural and
resource-rich province, as well as one of the most densely
populated areas in the country, according to Hui. Recent official
statistics show that more than 60 million people live in
Anhui which covers 135,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, the province is expected to reach
the national average in terms of the gross domestic product (GDP),
according to Hui.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, Anhui's GDP is expected to exceed the national average
and the province is projected to become one of major industrial and
economic powerhouses in the country, he noted. 
</P>
