<HEADLINE> Malaysian Former Deputy Prime Minister Detained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's former deputy
prime minister Anwar Ibrahim was detained by police at his house
here Sunday night, according to his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was seen taken out by police officers from his house and
driven off in a van and was expected to face charges of sexual
indecency, his lawyers Zainur Zakaria and Christopher Fernando
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was detained a day after his adopted brother and a former
speechwriter pleaded guilty in court Saturday to being sodomized
by Anwar.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was taken out of the house without handcuff to the shouts
of "Reform" by thousands of supporters, the Malaysian national
news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
Anwar addressed huge crowds of supporters earlier Sunday at the
National Mosque here and sections of the crowd later made their
way to the home of Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad but were
dispersed by anti-riot police.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was sacked as Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister
on September 2 amidst allegations of sexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
He was expelled from the ruling United Malays National
Organization of which he was deputy president, a day later for
having "low morals". 
</P>
</TEXT>
