<HEADLINE> Six Scientists Honored for Their Achievements in Science </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Six scientists will
receive this year's Albert Lasker awards for their discoveries
that identified the genetic basis of cancer and improved the
diagnosis and treatment of the disease.
</P>
<P>
According to an announcement made on 19 September in New York
by Albert and Mary Lasker Foundation, the recipients' findings and
subsequent research have established that alterations in genes are
the initial step leading to human cancer, and these discoveries
are helping to shape the design of future cancer therapies.
</P>
<P>
Clinical research awards are going to three scientists: Dr.
Alfred G. Knudson Jr., a former president of the Fox Chase Cancer
Center in Philadelphia; Dr. Peter C. Nowell, a professor of
pathology at the University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia, and
Dr. Janet D. Rowley of the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
Three recipients of basic medical research awards are Dr. Lee
Hartwell, president of the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center
and a geneticist at the University of Washington in Seattle; Dr.
Yoshio Masui of the University of Toronto, and Dr. Paul Nurse of
the Imperial Cancer Research Fund in London.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Daniel E. Koshland Jr. of the University of California at
Berkeley, will receive a special achievement award.
</P>
<P>
The awards will be made in New York on this Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
