<HEADLINE> Main Opposition Leads in District Polls in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The main opposition
Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML)
repeated its feat by leading again in the district elections held
last Friday, results from eight of the 11 districts show.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML bagged four seats of chairmen in Dailekh, Surkhet,
Mugu and Jumla and five seats of vice chairmen. It won the
majority of the membership in the four districts with 12 other
members in Dang, Banke, Bardiya and Piuthan.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Nepali Congress (NC) followed with three chairman
posts and one vice chairman post.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML), which
broke away from the CPN-UML in March this year and joined the
government in late August, did not win a single key post so far.
</P>
<P>
It lost even in Bardiya district, the constituency of its
General Secretary Bam Dev Gautam where the NC and the CPN-UML
formed an alliance.
</P>
<P>
Eleven chairmen and 11 vice chairmen along with 177 members are
scheduled to be elected for the district development committees
(DDC) in the 11 districts of mid-western development region.
</P>
<P>
Counting is yet to be completed in Dolpa, Humla and Kalikot.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission said that polls were conducted
peacefully in all the 11 districts.
</P>
<P>
Political parties formed alliance with one another in the
elections, which are considered crucial for them in the general
elections due to be held before November 1999.
</P>
<P>
DDC elections in these districts should have been held last
year but were stalled because elections for village development
committees (VDC) there were not completed due to violence by the
ultra-leftist guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Polls were held last year respectively for VDCs and
municipalities in May and DDCs in July in 56 of the 75 districts
in Nepal, in which the CPN-UML won a landslide victory.
</P>
<P>
But most of the mayors, deputy mayors, DDC chairmen, vice
chairmen and members elected at that time have joined the CPN-ML.
</P>
<P>
As the CPN-ML and the splinter group of National Democratic
Party (RPP) led by former prime minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand
are yet to be recognized by the Election Commission as national
parties, their candidates contested the elections as independents.
</P>
<P>
An independent backed by RPP (Chand) won a vice chairman post
in Banke district. 
</P>
</TEXT>
