<P>
LANZHOU, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Governments at all levels
have been urged to take effective measures to support development
of township enterprises, and to increase their added value by at
least 18 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
According to a circular issued by the Ministry of Agriculture,
the total added value of China's township enterprises
increased by 15.6 percent in the past eight months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, towship enterprises in 11 province-level areas have
expanded their added value by more than 18 percent, including
Hebei, Sichuan, Yunnan, Hunan, Gansu, Qinghai, Inner Mongolia and
Ningxia.
</P>
<P>
But it is still difficult to meet this year's target, because
negative effects of both serious floods this summer and Southeast
Asian financial crisis, according to a conference on the situation
of China's township enterprises which ended in Lanzhou, capital of
Gansu Province, today.
</P>
<P>
Township enterprises in flood-ravaged Hunan, Hubei, Jiangxi,
Anhui, Heilongjiang, Jilin provinces and Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region reduced their added value by 13.2 billion yuan this year.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture urged all local governments to
help township enterprises resume production and start
reconstruction immediately after flood waters recede.
</P>
<P>
The towship enterprises are advised to explore new export
markets, and they will be granted preferential treatment in export,
credit, taxation and technological upgrading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
