<DOCNO> XIE19980920.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Passenger Trains to Run Faster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 20 (Xinhua) -- China will raise the speed of
passenger trains again as of October 1, without tick price
hikes, with trains running at an average speed of 71.6 kilometers
per hour, up 4.5 km from the current level.
</P>
<P>
The highest speed of trains on the three major lines --
railways from Beijing to Guangzhou, Beijing to Shanghai, and
Beijing to Harbin -- will reach 140 to 160 km per hour.
</P>
<P>
A high-speed train on the Guangzhou-Shenzhen line will run at
an average speed of 200 km per hour. Trains on the
Hangzhou-Nanchang, Houma-Yueshan, Baoji-Zhongwei, Nanning-Kunming,
and Wuwei-Urumqi railways will also run faster, Chang Guozhi,
chief dispatcher of the Ministry of Railways, told a press
conference today.
</P>
<P>
A new railway operational map will be implemented to cater to
the change. Chang said that in line with it, the number of
passenger trains will increase to 1,108 pairs from 966.5 pairs on
the existing map; that of express trains will reach 88.5 pairs, up
40.5 percent; that of fast trains will double the current figure
to 80 pairs, and that of "arrive-in-one-night" trains will reach
228, 164 more than the current figure.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will operate more passenger trains running between
large cities, short-distance trains, holiday trains, and special
trains for non-local workers, he added.
</P>
<P>
Railways in southwest China, an area with short transport
capacities, have been upgraded, with the annual carrying capacity
of Baoji-Chengdu railway increasing by 1.3 million tons, that of
Xiangfan-Chongqing line by 1.7 million tons, and that of
Zhuzhou-Guiyang and Guiyang- Kunming lines by 3.5 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-Kowloon railway will focus on cargo transport,
because its designed annual cargo transport capacity is 70 million
tons, but only 20 million tons are used currently. More cargo
trains will be operated on the line in the future, Chang said,
adding that the Beijing-Guangzhou Railway will focus on passenger
transport.
</P>
<P>
Tong Anyan, director of the Transport Bureau of the Ministry of
Railways, said that his ministry has spent more than six billion
yuan (722.9 million US dollars) in infrastructure, upgrading the
crossings on Beijing-Guangzhou, Beijing-Shanghai, and
Beijing-Harbin lines.
</P>
<P>
The speed of China's trains was raised on April 1 last year, in
order to meet the neeeds of the national economy and sharpen the
competitive edge of railways on the whole transport market.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to raise the speed of trains according to
market demands," Chang noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
