<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal, India End Talks on Transit Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The secretary-level talks
between Nepal and India on renewing the transit treaty ended here
Sunday with good progress toward the finalization of the revised
treaty and its attached documents, the Nepali Ministry of Commerce
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides agreed to complete negotiations on the renewal
of the Treaty of Transit before its validity expired on December
5, 1998," the ministry said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides agreed that the principle of free, uninterrupted
and permanent access to sea for Nepal was the basis for transit
arrangements," it said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that during the four-day preliminary talks led by
their commerce secretaries, the two sides exchanged views on
Nepal's proposal for automatic renewal of the transit treaty
signed seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
As a land-locked country, Nepal largely depends on the transit
routes through India for foreign trade. At present, there are 15
transit points for Nepal.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides agreed on measures to further smoothen movement
of Nepalese transit cargo through the Indian territory," the
Nepali ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that it was agreed that with the exception of
a small number of specified sensitive items of export, Nepalese
export traffic-in-transit would not require duty insurance cover.
</P>
<P>
It said that the two sides reiterated that the duty insurance
in respect to import traffic-in-transit of Nepal would be required
only for specified sensitive items.
</P>
<P>
"Mechanism for the realization of duty lost due to diversion of
goods in India was also discussed in the meeting," the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, operating modalities relating to the Phulbari route,
which went into operation in September last year and provide Nepal
with an access to the Mongla port in Bangladesh through India,
were further clarified, it said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Indian side agreed to allow the movement of
petroleum products along this route subject to safety
requirements.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also had a useful exchange of views on the
implementation of the Trade Treaty and the Agreement of
Cooperation to Control Unauthorized Trade, the ministry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
