<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S Seminar on Intellectual Property Rights Closes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and U.S experts
expounded the relations between the protection of intellectual
property rights (IPR) and economic development during a seminar
that closed here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 150 experts also discussed the roles of the government,
enterprises and laws in protecting IPR and promoting economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was co-sponsored by the Chongqing municipal
government and the U.S. National Bureau of Asian Research.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, designed to intensify efforts to protect technical
inventions and handle the disputes in intellectual property
rights, was attended by experts and scholars from the academic
community and well-known enterprises such as Microsoft, IBM and
Legend of China.
</P>
<P>
Paul Liu, dean of Asia Pacific Legal Institute, noted that IPR
can spur economic development, which will in turn give IPR
higher additional values.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Qin Tianyuan from the Sichuan Provincial Academy of
Social Sciences said that China is facing two challenges in the
transitional period from an industrial economy to a
knowledge-based economy.
</P>
<P>
One is to catch up with the innovations in IPRs in the
international community; the other is to earnestly complete the
work to introduce the IPR system.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu, the National Bureau of Asian Research plans
to hold similar seminars in Shanghai and Beijing this year and
next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
