<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Turn Military Bases Into Civilian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is
planning to transform as many as 20 military bases around the
country into "economic develop hubs".
</P>
<P>
The Department of Public Works is negotiating with the World
Bank for one billion Rand (about 159 million U.S. dollars) to
fund the project, which was designed to create desperately needed
jobs, Business Times daily reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The redundant military bases will be set aside for land
reform, housing, commercial centers and industrial development,
Chief Director of State Property Holdings for the department, Gugu
Mazibuko, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The disposal of vast tracts of military land forms part of the
restructuring of the defense force, and coincides with the
planned closure of several large military bases and the proposed
retrenchment of about 30,000 permanent force members.
</P>
<P>
A task team made up of representatives from defense force and
public works departments, the non-governmental group for
environmental monitoring, has reportedly spent the past five
months finalizing a model for conversions.
</P>
<P>
The South African National Defense Force has about 60 large
military bases spread throughout the country, close to half of
which could eventually end up as major development initiatives,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
