<HEADLINE> Released Iranian Drivers Return to Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Five Iranian truck drivers
released by the Afghan Taliban militia arrived here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Iranians were set free by the Taliban on Saturday, Iran's
official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The release came apparently as a result of Pakistan's mediation
after an unexpected visit by Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj
Aziz to Tehran on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day visit, Aziz promised to help defuse the
mounting tensions between Iran and the Taliban following the
killing of eight Iranian diplomats and an IRNA reporter.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan supports the Afghan student militia group.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian drivers were among the claimed 35 taken captive by
the Taliban as they carried foodstuffs and medicines to Afghan
refugees suffering from the ongoing civil war. But the Taliban
said they were caught shipping weapons and ammunitions to its
opposition in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The relations between Iran and the Taliban deteriorated last
month after the militia rounded up and killed eight Iranian
diplomats and a journalist after it took over Mazar-e-Sherif, an
opposition stronghold in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Iran is a supporter of the opposition of Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban gave back to Iran the bodies of six diplomats and
the reporter on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Iran has massed more than 200,000 troops near the Afghan border
as domestic pressures for avenging the Taliban atrocities were
mounting.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani foreign minister has voiced Islamabad's readiness
to step up efforts to secure the return of the bodies of the
remaining two Iranian diplomats and the release of the Iranians
still held by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Iran said that more than 30 Iranian nationals, mainly truck
drivers and aid workers, are still in the hands of the Taliban.
</P>
</TEXT>
