<HEADLINE> Fighting Breaks out in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting broke out in
the Liberian capital Monrovia at the weekend, as government
security forces attempted to dislodge troops loyal to ex-warlord
David Roosevelt Johnson.
</P>
<P>
According to the Punch newspaper Sunday, the shooting began
Friday night when government troops moved on the residence of
Johnson at Camp Johnson Road, presumably to arrest him and his
troops which had been accused of plots to topple President
Charles Taylor.
</P>
<P>
Sounds of machine guns could be heard Friday night and
continued until early Saturday morning, the report said, quoting
Buari Ali, Press Secretary to the West African peace-keeping
force ECOMOG in Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
Security troops were being ferried to positions around Camp
Johnson Road and the Barclay training military barracks, as well
as Benson and Center Streets.
</P>
<P>
Liberia's Information Minister Joe Mulbah said in a special
broadcast that "dissident forces" were being round up following
sporadic exchange of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
He called on Monrovia residents not to harbor any dissident in
their midst.
</P>
<P>
This is the third attempt this year by Taylor to arrest the
ex-warlord, leading to heavy and sporadic shooting, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG troops, who had risen to such occasions in the
past, have apparently withdrawn from the troubled spots without
any official reason, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Roosevelt Johnson, leader of a faction of the United
Liberation Movement known as ULIMO-J, is a major rival of the
Taylor's National Patriotic Front of Liberia during the Liberia's
seven-year civil war.  
</P>
</TEXT>
