<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's Ronaldo da Costa
broke the 10-year-old world record for a marathon race Sunday in
Berlin, running through the heart of the German capitol in two
hours, six minutes and five seconds.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old took away 45 seconds out of the listed record
held by Ethiopia's Belayneh Densimo while running at one of the
world's fastest courses.
</P>
<P>
Densimo had recorded a 2:06.50 on April 17, 1988 in Rotterdam.
</P>
<P>
Belgium's Marleen Renders captured the women's race in 2:25.22
for the third best time in the history of the Berlin Marathon.
</P>
<P>
The event has grown in size in recent years and with 28,000
runners at the start is now the world third largest city marathon
behind London and New York. 
