<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Freed Iranians Leave for Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Five Iranians, released by
the Afghan Taliban Saturday, left for Tehran Sunday morning after
several months in detention in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The five Iranians were brought to Islamabad Saturday evening in
a special Pakistan air force plane from the southern Afghan city
of Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
Taliban leader Muhammad Omar had ordered the release of the
five Iranians two weeks after the release of the same number of
Iranians amid growing border tension between Iran and the Taliban
over the killing of Iranian diplomats in the northern Afghan town
of Mazar-i-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban had freed five Iranians on September 3.
</P>
<P>
About 40 Iranians are reported to be still in custody of the
Taliban. They were arrested when the Taliban militia overran
Mazar-i-Sharif, the stronghold of the anti-Taliban Northern
Alliance, on August 8.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban blamed the Iranians for bringing arms for the
Northern Alliance, while Iran said they had brought only
humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
Maulvi Rehmatullah, a senior Taliban representative in
Islamabad, asked Iran to take some practical steps following the
release of five Iranians and immediately withdraw its troops from
the border.
</P>
<P>
He said that deployment of troops by Iran near the Afghan
border has created tension in the whole region.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want second war with any country but desire to settle
differences through negotiations with Iran," he told reporters
here on return from Kandahar with the freed Iranians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
