<HEADLINE> Rebels Claim to Have Occupied 40 Percent of Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 20 (Xinhua) --Rebels in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) claimed that 40 percent of the
country with a population of 16 million of people have been under
their control, Tanzania's "Sunday Observer" said.
</P>
<P>
A major leader of the rebels, Earnest Wamba dia Wamba,
who told the newspaper on Friday in a telephone interview from the
eastern Congolese town of Goma, asserted that the area under control
is larger than the total territories of Uganda, Rwanda and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Wamba said his 60,000-strong troops, battling 140,000 soldiers and
militia commanded by President Laurent Kabila, have controlled 10
towns and cities and are still marching forward on various fronts of
the third largest African country.
</P>
<P>
He said Goma, Kalemie, Kisangani, Bukavu, Beni, Butembo, Uvira and
Bunia have been captured, and their troops, have advanced beyond the
third largest city of Kisangani to the west. In addition, the rebel
troops are advancing to Kindu and heading towards the major business
town of Lubumbashi.
</P>
<P>
Wamba, who was a history professor with the University of Dar es
Salaam, had requested to leave between July 25 and August 9 for "attending
a meeting" but failed to return in time. He has been been sacked by
the university administration because of absenteeism.
</P>
<P>
Wamba was picked up last month to be a political leader of the
rebels. He said the war waged against Kabila is to bring democratic
change in the country.
</P>
<P>
It is said the professor, who went through a rough terrain during
the rule of Mobutu Sese Seko, was once placed behind bars for
being active in the opposition camp.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ugandan, Tanzanian and Zamibian Presidents held talks in
Entebbe in Uganda on Saturday, appealing for an immediate ceasefire in
the DRC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
