<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Artist Destroys Printing Blocks to Make His Pictures Out of Print </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Lu Fang, a Chinese artist of
wood-block print, destroyed the printing blocks of his two
pictures today to make his works out of print.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-five-year-old Lu, from Chinese Academy of Fine Arts,
explained his deed which has never been done in China that he
wanted to prove that each of the two pictures has only 25 prints,
and therefore increase their value.
</P>
<P>
Wood-block print, a picture printed from an engraved or etched
plate, is an art form originated in China. Currently, a practice
in the international wood-block print circle is that artists must
promise to the society their pictures printed within a limited
number.
</P>
<P>
"Destroying the printing blocks is the best way to make the
promise," said Lu.
</P>
<P>
Both of the pictures feature the West Lake, a well-known scenic
spot in Hangzhou which is capital of east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 60 works of Lu, also in the subject of West Lake, were
on show in Hangzhou today, and two pictures have been housed in
the West Lake Traditional Chinese Painting Museum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
