<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Glorious Life of Yang Shangkun (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yang entered Shanghai University, an institution under Party
leadership, in the spring of 1926 and actively participated in
planning the first and second armed uprisings of Shanghai
workers.
</P>
<P>
He entered Moscow's Sun Yat-sen University in November that
same year and thereafter systematically studied theories of
Marxism and Leninism. He served as a class monitor and was a
member of the Party subcommittee and deputy director of the
university's propaganda department.
</P>
<P>
Yang and Li Bozhao were married in the Soviet Union in 1929,
and the following year he commenced postgraduate studies at the
Research Institute of Chinese Affairs. He also worked as a
translator for the Chinese representative of the Workers
International.
</P>
<P>
Yang returned to the motherland in 1931 at a time when the
nation was beset with deep misery. He served as director
of the Propaganda Department for the All-China Federation of Trade
Unions and as secretary of both the Party and Youth League of the
Shanghai Association of Trade Unions.
</P>
<P>
He worked diligently to reestablish trade unions and recruit
Party members in areas subject to the vicious control of the
Kuomintang.
</P>
<P>
After the September 18th Incident in 1931 that marked the
beginning of Japan's occupation of northeast China, Yang served as
director of the Propaganda Department of the Jiangsu CPC
Provincial Committee at the time, and later held a similar
position for the CPC Central Committee. His work centered on
directing workers movements and the anti-Japanese campaign for
national salvation.
</P>
<P>
Yang was assigned to the central revolutionary base area in
Ruijin, east China's Jiangxi Province, in January 1933. He served
as director of the Propaganda Department of the Central Bureau of
the Central Soviet Area and helped edit the Party's institutional
publications, including the "Red China" and "Struggle."
</P>
<P>
Yang was assigned in February to a position as head of the Red
China News Service, the predecessor to the Xinhua News Agency, and
in March became deputy president of the Marxism Communist
University founded by the Central Bureau for the Soviet Area.
</P>
<P>
He was assigned to the Chinese Workers and Peasants Red Army in
June and worked as director of the Political Department for the
First Front Army. Soon thereafter he was sent to the front-lines and
served under General Zhu De and Political Commissar Zhou
Enlai.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980920.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Glorious Life of Yang Shangkun (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yang became political commissar of the the Third Army Corps of
the Red Army in January 1934, and later in the month was elected
an alternate member of the CPC Central Committee during the Fifth
Plenary Session of the CPC Sixth Central Committee. He was also
elected a member of the Central Executive Committee of the
Chinese Soviet Republic.
</P>
<P>
He joined Third Army Corps Commander Peng Dehuai in winning a
series of decisive victories during the fifth anti-encirclement
campaign in the Central Soviet Area. He attached great importance
to coordination between units, properly handled various
contradictions and united his troops to fulfill all battle tasks.
</P>
<P>
Yang and Peng Dehuai led the Third Army Corps on monumental
Long March from Jiangxi Province beginning on October 17,
1934. The Third Army's success in breaking through four enemy
blockade lines won high praise from the Revolutionary Military
Commission under the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
In January 1935, Yang attended the enlarged meeting of the CPC
Central Committee's Political Bureau in the city of Zunyi in
southwestern Guizhou Province. He criticized Bo Gu and Li De for
serious command mistakes and expressed his full support to Mao
Zedong's correct view concerning the matter.
</P>
<P>
Yang and Peng exhibited great flexibility in carrying out Mao's
military strategies and tactics while leading the Third Army Corps
in many crucial battles. The Corps launched a successful offensive
to capture the Loushan Pass and joined the First Army Corps of the
Red Army in retaking Zunyi in the first significant victory won by
the First Front Army of the Red Army during the Long March.
</P>
<P>
The two commanders carefully assessed the rapidly changing
battle situation and offered several suggestions which were
adopted by Mao and the Central Military Commission. Yang and Peng
performed meritoriously to support China's revolution during a
critical period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980920.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Ross Mission: Some Headway, No Breakthrough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Says U.S. Middle East peace
envoy Dennis Ross: "We have made some headway, but there is still
work to be done."
</P>
<P>
This most often-repeated line during his 11 days of shuttle
diplomacy in the region may well be used to sum up his whole trip,
which ended Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Quite interestingly, the most, if not the only, noteworthy
progress was made in his last-minute effort prior to his departure
for journey home.
</P>
<P>
After separate talks with Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu Saturday night, Ross was relieved to hear that the two
agreed in principle to hold direct talks.
</P>
<P>
Both Arafat and Netanyahu will be in New York later this week
to attend the 53rd General Assembly of the United Nations.
Washington has expected a summit to take place so the two could
seal a deal over the long overdue Israeli withdrawal from the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
This was actually the main goal of Ross' mission. But to avoid
possible embarrassment, Washington was so discreet as to refuse to
spell it out as Ross flew to the region on September 9.
</P>
<P>
In an exhaustive effort to bridge the gaps between the two
sides, Ross has held several rounds of talks with Arafat and
Netanyahu, as well as other senior Palestinian and Israeli
officials. He also paid short visits to Egypt and Jordan, the two
important mediators in the region, to brief their leaders on his
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Despite wild speculation and conflicting reports, Ross'
last-minute achievement did signal that some progress has been
made during his stay on the Israeli-Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations said that
although absent of an official agreement, the Palestinians have in
effect accepted the idea of a nature reserve on a 3 percent of
land in the Judean Desert to be turned over to them.
</P>
<P>
Israel proposed the nature reserve after it rejected an
American initiative which calls for a 13 percent Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank, insisting that parts of the land be
under different treatment from the others.
</P>
<P>
The scope of the Israeli withdrawal has been one of the most
sticky point in the negotiations since the two sides resumed
direct talks two months ago. The Palestinians opposed to any
change to the U.S. proposal while Netanyahu's right-wing allies
threatened to topple him if he agreed to anything exceeding 9
percent.
</P>
<P>
To narrow Israeli and Palestinian differences over the status
of the nature reserve, Ross presented a formula under which the
nature reserve would meet what both sides are calling
"international standards," sources said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli sources said Netanyahu intended to appoint
National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, one of the leading
hawk in the government, as foreign minister in exchange for his
approval of the 13 percent pullback.
</P>
<P>
On another outstanding issue of security cooperation between
Israel and the Palestinians, sources said that the Palestinians
appear ready to accept key ideas that Israel and U.S. put
together in an early July draft to enhance a memorandum of
understanding originally formulated last year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-brokered memorandum was signed in December but
Netanyahu rejected it, saying it was not detailed enough to be
effective. The July draft included some changes addressing
Israeli security concerns, but the Palestinians refused to endorse
it, blaming that the U.S. and Israel did it without consulting
them.
</P>
<P>
Ross also scored in reactivating Israeli-Palestinian
committees, which work on other interim issues such as a
Palestinian airport in Gaza and the safe passage between Gaza and
the West Bank, after they broke off four months ago.
</P>
<P>
Progress aside, however, the envoy returned to Washington
without a concrete agreement. Disputes still exist in many areas,
although Ross called them "technical issues."
</P>
<P>
The two sides are still bargaining over the responsibility the
PNA will have in the so-called "nature reserve;" they are
disputing over the security control over and the route of the
safe passage; the Palestinians said they have fulfill their
commitment to fight terrorism but Israel said it is not
enough. There are many uncertainties ahead.
</P>
<P>
But perhaps the only certainty is that a lot of work still
needs to be done before an agreement can be finalized, and thus a
real breakthrough in the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
