<HEADLINE> Oil Companies Increase Exploratory Activities in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 20 (Xinhua) -- High hopes are being raised
over possible discovery of crude oil in the northern part of
Nigeria as multi-national oil companies have increased
exploratory activities in the region.
</P>
<P>
Three oil companies operating in 21 blocks have drilled wells
over 2,500 square kilometers of seismic survey in Gombe, Plateau,
Bauchi and Adamawa states, according to a Sunday Times report.
</P>
<P>
Results of the data collected from these surveys suggest that
"several of the elements necessary for an oil accumulation may be
present" in the region, the report said, but officials have not
come to say categorically that oil had been found.
</P>
<P>
Oil companies operating in northern Nigeria include Shell
Nigeria Petroleum Nigeria Ltd., Chevron Petroleum Nigeria Ltd.
and ELf Petroleum Nigeria Ltd.
</P>
<P>
A top Chevron official told the paper that his company is
scheduled to commence drilling in three blocks before the end of
the year and is going ahead to drill its first exploratory well
during the last quarter of 1999 in its oil prospecting areas.
</P>
<P>
Chevron's Community Relations Manager, Deji Haastrup, who has
gone on a sensitization trip to its prospecting areas, said that
any success recorded during the drilling of wells would benefit
the company, the communities and the country as a whole.
</P>
<P>
By next year, Chevron would have committed more than 18
million U.S. Dollars into the search for the black gold north of
the Niger State in the country.
</P>
