<HEADLINE> Besenyei Cements Lead in Aerobatics Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Talented Peter Besenyei of
Hungary fortified his lead by claiming the second leg of the FAI
China Cup aerobatics grand prix here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The lanky 42-year-old Hngarian, who created knife-edge skill
which is now very popular in aerobatics, garnered 8.368 points to
win the second leg, building up his overall tally to 24.
</P>
<P>
The unexpected drizzle forced the cancellation of the
competition on Sunday. "The weather is too lousy and the
visibility is rather poor," said Jean Louis Monnet, Chief
Executive officer of Federation Aeronautique Internationale (FAI)
World Grand Prix of Aviation.
</P>
<P>
"So we had to cancel the competition today and the results of
yesterday's performance are final, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Nikolay Timofeev of Russia, who challenged Besenyei strongly
on Saturday, finished second on 8.308 with his overall tally up
to 20. Another Russian Viktor Tchmal came in third on 8.302 and
his overall tally increased to 16.
</P>
<P>
The winner of every leg will be awarded 12 points to the
overall tally, with the runner-up and third finisher takes 10 and
8, respectively.
</P>
<P>
"The pilots' scores are close," said chief judge Quintin
Hawthorne. "Besenyei is very experienced and his advantage is the
ability to interpret the accompanying music which is the main
part of the competition."
</P>
<P>
The drizzle failed to douse the local's craze for the
aerobatics performance, which become a smash hit here. Over 20
thousands spectators braved the rain to see the display of the
pilots and the Golden Dreams Aerobatic Display Team.
</P>
<P>
"I can't believe my eyes," said Chen Jiayan, a 15-year-old
sixth grader of Nanjing No.4 primary school. "The display is just
too excellent to believe and the 150 yuan (about 20 U.S. dollars)
I spent on the ticket is worthwhile"
</P>
<P>
The next leg of the grand prix will be held from 25 to 27
September in Ji'nan, the capital city of Shandong province in
east China.
</P>
<P>
The grand prix, which hailed by FAI president Eilif Ness as
the greatest festival of competitive aerobatics ever held, drew
the top 24 finishers of the world championships held last August.
</P>
<P>
The contestants, in the grand prix to be ended on November
2nd, will go on making tour matches and displays at Tianjing,
Shijiazhuang, Zhengzhou, Wuhan and Changsha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
