<HEADLINE> Albania to Take Measures to Avoid Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian government has
decided to take measures to stablize the situation in the Balkan
country and avoid new crisis and conflicts, the newspaper Voice of
People reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During a cabinet meeting held Saturday night, Prime Minister
Fatos Nano said that in the coming three months, the government
will carry out a package of measures to stablize the country,
balance the financial system and pass the draft of new
constitution so that the country would not face new crisis.
</P>
<P>
To realize these purposes, Nano added, there should be mutual
trust between the parties, between the individuals and the
institutions and between the citizens and the government.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also admitted that his government has
shortcomings in the process of restoring social order, fighting
against corruption and smuggling, and fulfilling tasks and social
investment.
</P>
<P>
While reporting on the violences occurred last Sunday and
Monday, Public Security Minister Perikli Teta confirmed that five
people were killed and 57 injured in the unrest.
</P>
<P>
The violences, the worst in the past 18 months, erupted in
Tirana on September 13 and soon escalated after the assassination
of the popular opposition leader Azem Hajdari. 
</P>
