<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola Production Suspended in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Production of Coca-Cola and other
soft drinks at the plant of Zambia Bottlers, local manufacturer of
Coca-Cola Company, has been suspended because of poor sales following
the recent hike of their retail prices.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Sunday quoted the Lusaka-based company's
highly-placed sources as saying that statistics showed that an average
of 80 percent of all products sent for marketing are returning to the
plant.
</P>
<P>
The sources, who did not clarify the date when the production was
suspended, said if the situation persisted and the company's talks
with the Zambian government on reduction of its excise duty flopped,
the management sector would be forced to take drastic measures such as
permanently laying off staff.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Bottlers increased Coca-Cola's retail price from 500 Kwacha
to 900 (one U.S. Dollars equals 2000 Kwacha) two weeks ago after the
government failed to honor an agreement concluded with the Coco-Cola
Company last May.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Zambian government would reduce the
company's excise duty from 25 to five percent while the company
pledged to invest 75 million dollars to expand its operations in the
country.
</P>
<P>
However, the Zambian government failed to keep its promise and the
Coca-Cola Company later decided to suspended its investment program
and raised the price of its drinks.
</P>
<P>
The price hike of the drink was followed by initially an estimated
30 percent fall in sales and the flooding of Zimbabwe-made Cokes into
the Zambian market last week.
</P>
<P>
Comparatively in the central African region, according to the local
paper, Zambia's tax regime ranks highest among five other countries
namely Zimbabwe, Malawi, Namibia, Botswana and Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Zambia charges 25 percent excise duty on all wholesale products,
17.5 percent value added tax on wholesale and another 17.5 percent on
all retail sales. However, Zimbabwe demands only 22.5 percent on
manufacturing, while Malawi charges on 20 percent on tax. And the duty
charged by other three countries ranges from 20 to 10 percent
altogether.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
