<DOCNO> XIE19980920.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Pupil May Be Expelled for Not Paying School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- School fees in South
Africa are not compulsory and no action could be taken against
any pupil whose parents could not afford to pay, a senior
education department official said at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Mary Metcalfe, member of the Executive Council in Gauteng
Province's Education Department, said that no pupil may be
expelled from any school for not paying school fees.
</P>
<P>
She made the remarks in reply to a written question by the
opposition Democratic Party in legislature last week.
</P>
<P>
Metcalfe said it was the right of any pupil aged between seven
to 15 to attend public schools irrespective of their parents
ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
She said parents should also negotiate to pay a manageable
fee, but if parents were unable to pay school fees, they should
write to the schools' government body or discuss their problem
with the principal.
</P>
<P>
She said the failure to pay fees was no offence and did not
warrant suspension or expulsion, noting that only the head of
school department had the right to expel a pupil for school and
only for serious offenses.
</P>
<P>
However, she added, the provincial education department had
the right to intervene in public hcool and reverse the decision
to expel a pupil.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
