<HEADLINE> No "Counter-Productive" Actions: Indonesia Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Home Affairs
Minister Syarwan Hamid has urged all people to restrain themselves
from taking any "counter-productive actions" that can worsen the
current difficult situation, Antara news agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"It is better for us to build common vision to safeguard and
prevent the country from deepening economic crisis and work
together to restore security and order for the sake of peace and
prosperity," Hamid was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hamid made the statement in Ambon, capital of Maluku province,
late Saturday in response to reporters' questions about the
mounting students' protests against the government's measures and
policies in dealing with the country's current problems.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, the world's fourth most populous country with more
than 200 million people, has been hit by the economic turmoil
since mid-1997 as a result of the regional financial and economic
crisis which flared up in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Students in Jakarta and other cities held rallies this month to
protest the spiraling prices of basic commodities. They urged
President B.J. Habibie to take concrete measures to resolve the
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after Brig. Gen. Paula Renyaan was
installed as Maluku vice governor, Hamid said the best way for
people to face the current situation is to restrain themselves
from taking any "counter-productive actions" which would damage
the country's credibility abroad.
</P>
<P>
On the government's political agenda, he said the government
has clear items in its agenda which will consistently be carried
out.
</P>
<P>
The agenda items include the holding of a special session of
the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), the country's highest
legislative body, in November this year, a general election in May
1999 and the MPR's general assembly at the end of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
