<HEADLINE> Permanent Monitoring in Iraq Goes on Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. permanent monitoring
system in Iraq is running on smoothly with no problems at all, a
U.N. source said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Iraqi News Agency, Neils Karlston,
director of the U.N. Special Commission on disarming Iraq, said
the monitoring system is still working undisturbedly and the
monitoring inspectors are doing their job at Iraqi sites every day.
</P>
<P>
He added that the cooperation between Iraq and the commission
is smoothly going on.
</P>
<P>
Iraq decided to suspend cooperation with UNSCOM on August 5,
demanding lifting oil embargo, recomposing the special commission
and moving its headquarters from New York to Vienna to avoid
U.S. influence.
</P>
<P>
It also announced that the permanent monitoring would be
allowed to go ahead in a bid to show good intentions and refute
interpreting the Iraqi decision as a non-commitment to the
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi people are suffering from the eight-year-old,
crippling U.N. economic sanctions imposed after Baghdad's troops
invaded Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
