<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Allocates 912 Million Dollars for Post-Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
allocated 42.88 billion taka (about 912.34 million U.S. dollars)
for post-flood rehabilitation programs in the country.
</P>
<P>
The funds would be generated through readjusting the Annual
Development Program (ADP) and the donors' aid, to reconstruct
infrastructure damaged by floods and create jobs in rural areas,
The Bangladesh Observer daily reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at a high-level meeting on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
State Minister for Planning Mohiuddin Khan Alamgir said the
meeting did not slash the ADP size at 136 billion taka (2.89
billion dollars) for 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
"The size of the ADP would remain the same but it has been
re-focused towards rehabilitation programs," Alamgir was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Funds from less important projects would be diverted to
projects directly involved in rehabilitation schemes, he said.
</P>
<P>
The most important task was to implement the massive
reconstruction and rehabilitation work so that people could get
job in the rural areas, and gratuitous relief and vulnerable group
feeding would continue in the affected areas, according to the
state minister.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina directed
ministries concerned to start immediately Food-for-Work and Test
Relief in the affected areas for providing employment
opportunities to the jobless poor, wherever flood water receded.
</P>
<P>
She laid stress on creating employment opportunities in the
rural areas by starting reconstruction and repair of the damaged
roads, bridges and culverts, schools, colleges and clinics.
</P>
<P>
The government's agriculture rehabilitation program included
ensuring availability of seeds and fertilizer free of cost, and
providing cash help to the farmers, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The government earlier announced a 32 billion-taka (680.85
million dollars) farm loan program for the flood-affected farmers.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has been badly hit by flooding this year, with
three-fourths of its territory inundated and nearly 30 million of
its 127-million population seriously affected, causing an
estimated loss of over 3.4 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
