<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops Hour-by-hour Plan for Gymnastics Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese organizers of
the 1999 Gymnastics World Championships reported an hour-by-hour
"extraordinarily advanced plan" for the tournament to be held
here next year to the visiting officials from the International Gy
mnastics Federation (FIG) on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Hardy Fink, president of the Men's Technical Committee (MTC),
and Jackie K. Fie, president of the Women's Technical Committee
(WTC), attended the one-hour-and-a-half in-depth presentation
which explains the preparation work for the coming Gymnastics
Worlds.
</P>
<P>
The inspecting top FIG officials, who will also stay out the
six-day China Cup tournament which starts tomorrow, both said
they are very much impressed by China's advanced plan.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very well-prepared plan," said Fie, "I'm very happy
about that."
</P>
<P>
"I have to say it's an extraordinarily advanced plan. I'm
grateful for your particular hard work," Fink added.
</P>
<P>
The competition schedule was an hour-by-hour one which
features opening ceremony, closing banquet, team and individual
competitions, award ceremonies and even break time for judges and
gymnasts between sessions.
</P>
<P>
The nine-day tournament, slated for october 8-16 in 1999,
still has an entire year away from now.
</P>
<P>
Miao Zhongyi, director of the competition department, said
they made a maxium programme as they think the 1999 Worlds would
attract an unprecedented number of participating countries.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin organization committee had earlier confirmed they
would pay for accommondation of participating gymnasts.
</P>
<P>
But both Fie and Fink told the organizers that they reserve
the right to manipulate the schedule "in a fair way" and make
some adjustments since they don't think there will be so many
entrances in the first place and "a less strenuous and less full
programme" would be more fitting.
</P>
<P>
In the financial part of the plan, the budget for the 1999
Worlds, which has been nation-wide billed as the last big sports
gala held in China in the 20th century, will hit 60 million yuan
(about 7.5 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
From tomorrow, the two FIG technical presidents will be shown
around Tianjin Sports Center, the site for next year's Worlds,
which includes an 8,000-seat main competition hall, a training
hall and a warmup hall, the longest walk between the three halls
only 50 meters. The Center also provides a comprehensive service
center for gymnasts, reporters, judges and officials.
</P>
<P>
Four hotels have been set aside exclusively to the
tournament's use, including tow five-stars for FIG officials, one
four-star for reporters and one three-star for gymnasts, with the
longest distance to the Center being two kilometers.
</P>
<P>
"We will listen carefully to FIG's feedback opinions and make
further improvements to our programme," Miao said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
