<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Take Action on NLD's Parliament Convening </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government has
warned the National League for Democracy (NLD) that the party
could face serious action if it tried to convene a parliament
unilaterally, according to an official Information Sheet issued
here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Ambassador to the United States U Tin Winn, in an
interview with the Myanmar Monitor published in Washington DC
Tuesday, said the unilateral action is not only unlawful but also
treacherous according to the country's criminal codes.
</P>
<P>
"In order not to have to take drastic action, like outlawing
the NLD and arresting leaders of the party, the authorities have
tried to diffuse the situation by inviting some NLD members from
outside of the Yangon area to come to the guest house and discuss
the situation and the NLD's intention," he said.
</P>
<P>
A People's Parliament Elected in the 1990 Multi-Party General
Election of Myanmar was unilaterally formed here Wednesday with U
Saw Mya Aung, chairman of the Rakhine League for Democracy (RLD),
as chairman of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
A 10-member Representing Committee of the Parliament Elected in
the Election (RCPEE) was also formed earlier on Wednesday to
arrange for the convening of the People's Parliament. NLD Chairman
U Aung Shwe was chosen as the committee's chairman with U Than Tun
and U Aye Tha Aung as secretaries. Other members include U Tin Oo,
the NLD vice-chairman, and Aung San Suu Kyi, NLD's general
secretary.
</P>
<P>
The ruling State Peace and Development Council on Friday poured
scorn on moves by the opposition "People Parliament" to take over
the government, declaring that it will continue to rule the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
