<HEADLINE> Myanmar Wishes to Restore Relations With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar wishes to restore
traditionally good relations with the United States and get them
back on track, according to an official Information Sheet issued
here Sunday, quoting Myanmar's Ambassador to the U.S. U Tin Winn.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by the Myanmar Monitor published in Washington DC
Tuesday, U Tin Winn said: "The current state of U.S.-Myanmar
relations are at their lowest ebb."
</P>
<P>
For restoration of the two countries' relations, he called for
Washington's recognition that the present Myanmar government --
the State Peace and Development Council -- is acting in the
interest of the nation and the people.
</P>
<P>
He urged Washington to have a better appreciation of the recent
history of Myanmar, especially the reasons for the military's
leading role, saying that Myanmar's Armed Forces are "different"
from others' in the world.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. should realize that democracy cannot be built in a
day, in a month or in a year," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that there are many fields where the two
countries can cooperate with each other such as narcotic drug
suppression, health, education and exploration of natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
As a first step, the U.S. should seriously consider lifting
sanctions, otherwise it would be very difficult for them to
cooperate in the economic field, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar is also complaining that the U.S. is
blocking loans to the country from all international financial
institutions including the World Bank, the International Monetary
Fund and the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. imposed economic sanctions on Myanmar in May 1997,
banning new investments in the country.
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. companies have reportedly begun withdrawing their
investments in Myanmar since 1996. Those already pulled out
include the Pepsi-Cola, Eddie Bauer, Liz Claiborne and Texaco Oil
Company.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the Atlantic Richfields Oil Company of the
U.S. also decided in August to follow suit in the near future.
</P>
</TEXT>
