<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Albania Not Affected by Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment continued
to flow into Albania despite the political turmoil which has been
striking the country over the past week, the Albanian Telegraphic
Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Albanian Minister of Public Works and Transport Gaqo
Apostoli, the agency said that foreign investment in Albania has
not been interrupted and on the contrary it is recording a new
high.
</P>
<P>
Apostoli said, "Funds are available for the construction of
road segments north-south and east-west."
</P>
<P>
"Some 21 million ECU (about 24.36 million U.S. dollars) are
allocated for the Durres-Rrogozhina highway project while 20
million ECU (about 23.2 million dollars) for the
Rrogozhina-Elbasan highway project and another 6 million ECU (about
6.96 million dollars) for Milot-Lezhe," he said.
</P>
<P>
Work on the Durres-Rrogozhina axis is being done by
Sarandopulos-Falcione, in Rrogozhina-Elbasan axis by BE-HA-SE and
Milot-Lezhe by Falcione.
</P>
<P>
"A tender was organized for the Librazhd-Qukes segment which
was estimated at 13 million ECU (about 15.08 million dollars). Now
we are going to sign the contract with the foreign constructive
companies," Apostoli said.
</P>
<P>
Other investments are those for the Durres-Sukth highway worth
23 million ECU (26.7 million dollars). The winning companies
"Ruscollo" and "Italstrade" will construct the Sukth-Vore section
at a cost of 14 million ECU (16.2 million dollars) while some
20 million ECU (23.2 million dollars) will be invested for the
Rrogozhin-Lushnje highway.
</P>
<P>
Work on part of the Fush-Kruje-Mamurras highway is ready for
start as some 3.2 million ECU (3.72 million dollars) are
allocated, Apostoli said.
</P>
<P>
Albanian opposition parties have been organizing demonstrations
in the capital following the assassination of a leading opposition
deputy, Azem Hajdari, last week near the Democratic Party
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The protesters are demanding the resignation of Prime Minister
Fatos Nano. 
</P>
