<HEADLINE> Fourteen Countries Urge Prevention of AIDS in Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Fourteen countries appealed
here Saturday to pay more attention to prevent the Acquired Immune
Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS) in the army.
</P>
<P>
Military leaders from 13 European countries and the United
States urged military organizations in the world to draft
strategies on the prevention of the HIV virus in accordance with
their own countries' situation, the Bulgarian news agency PAP
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 14 countries signed a declaration on military and civilian
cooperation to curb HIV and AIDS outbreaks at the end of
the international anti-AIDS conference Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The four-day meeting on "Young People's Prevention and AIDS in
Armed Forces" discussed the prevention of AIDS in the army.
</P>
<P>
Under the declaration, the participants called on the military
doctors to protect the AIDS carriers or patients and provide them
with medical services and social support. They also asked
countries to strengthen cooperation on medical care, information
exchange and money supply.
</P>
<P>
According to experts of the Bulgarian military academy, there
are 17 AIDS carriers in the army, out of the total 240 in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Albania, Bulgaria, Croatia, Greece, Italy,
Macedonia, Moldova, Romania, Russia, the United States, Slovenia,
Turkey, Ukraine, and Yugoslavia attended the meeting. 
</P>
