<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy to Boost Economic Growth in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Italy's 1999 budget offers tax
breaks and other incentives to develop its economy in the south.
</P>
<P>
The budget bill, due to be approved by the cabinet on Friday,
plans to set up an agency named Agensud with a view to
coordinating development and job creation initiatives in the
economically depressed south.
</P>
<P>
In some areas of southern Italy, unemployment rate doubles the
national average of 12.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the budget bill, 36 trillion lire (about 21.5
billion U.S. dollars) will be set aside for the development in
southern Italy in the next four years.
</P>
<P>
Agensud will be responsible for managing the funds and will
bring together the seven organizations currently in charge of
overseeing development in the south.
</P>
<P>
The bill also proposes some cost-saving plans for the national
railway service and the Post Office.
</P>
<P>
It also suggests the number of civil service employees be cut
by one percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Italian Premier Romano Prodi hopes that the budget bill could
win approval from Communist Refoundation Party leader Fausto
Bertinotti, who has threatened to withdraw his support from the
government unless it changes its social policies drastically.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's center-left coalition relies on the hard-left parties'
34 deputies in the Lower House to pass legislations, including the
budget.
</P>
<P>
Bertinotti has been demanding for months that the 1999 budget
should do more to promote jobs and support the poor. He said if
the budget fails to satisfy his demands, he will switch over to
the opposition, which will bring down the coalition government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
