<HEADLINE> Slovakian Economy Maintain Fast Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Slovakia's gross domestic
product (GDP) grew 6.1 percent to 347.8 billion koruna (about 10.2
billion U.S. dollars) in the first half of this year over the same
period of last year, the Slovak Statistics Bureau announced Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The bureau predicted that the annual GDP growth rate will stand
at 5.6 percent in 1998, the fifth year of continued growth from
1994.
</P>
<P>
The Slovak economic situation has been the best one of the 12
central east European countries thanks to the measures taken by
the state to push the market economy, strengthen the macroeconomic
regulation and adjust the industrial structure after separating
from Czechoslovakia in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The country also improved its taxation policy to encourage
export and attract foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the average monthly income of staff and workers
went up 10.6 percent to 9,444 koruna (about 277.8 U.S. dollars) in
the first half of the year over the same time of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
