<HEADLINE> Emergency to Be Extended in Chiapas, Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The state of emergency
will last one more week in some part of the southern Mexican state
of Chiapas, where hunger and epidemics have occurred, humanitarian
agencies said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Authorities and non-government organizations maintain different
versions about the effects of the rains on the coast of Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
The central government said that 172 people died and about 400
were missing, while the municipal authorities reported at least
413 deaths and more than 650 people missing.
</P>
<P>
But both agreed that the final casualties would possibly surpass
one thousand.
</P>
<P>
Despite the subsiding water level, it was still impossible to
reach many isolated areas, making estimation of damages difficult.
</P>
<P>
Rescue groups were busy burying the dead to prevent the spread
of diseases.
</P>
<P>
Denying any outbreak of cholera or plague, the government
admitted that there were cases of conjunctivitis, dermatitis,
diarrhea and gastrointestinal affections.
</P>
<P>
The Chiapas Sanitation Overseeing Committee said that 2,023
doctors and nurses are now attending victims in refuges and
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Felipe Arizmendi, bishop of the Tapachula diocese, said on
Friday that there was famine in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Social Security Mexican Institute opened mobile stores to
step up supply of necessary staples and to distribute 470 tons of
food that have reached the town of Puerto Madero in Tapachu.
</P>
<P>
The National Liberation Zapatista Army, which some days ago
announced it would donate money to flood victims, on Friday night
sent 10 tons of corn to the Motozintla municipality, one of the
most damaged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
