<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Accelerates Hydropower Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 20 (Xinhua) -- China has drawn a blueprint
for constructing four large hydropower projects by 2010, and four
big power firms are to be organized to run them by the State Power
Corp, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The projects include the Gongboxia Hydropower Station, with an
installed capacity of 1.5 million kilowatts; the Laxiwa Hydropower
Station, with an installed capacity of 3.72 million kilowatts; the
Longtan Hydropower Station on the upper reaches of the Hongshui
River in Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, with a capacity of 5.4
million kilowatts; the Xiaowan Hydropower Station on the Lancang
river in Yunnan Province, with a capacity of 4.2 million kilowatts;
and the Sanbanxi Hydropower Station on the Yuanshui River in Hunan
Province, with a capacity of 1.5 million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
The total investment to the projects is estimated at 60 billion
yuan (7.23 billion US dollars), according to Zhang Xuezhi, director
of the hydropower development department with the State Power Corp.
</P>
<P>
China's hydropower capacity accounts for only 24 percent of the
country's total power generating capacity. Seventy percent of
electricity is generated by coal-fired stations, seriously
polluting the air and increasing transportation costs.
</P>
<P>
The State Development Planning Commission is considering
separating the operation of grids from that of power plants,
thereby creating a fair competitive environment for power
producers. Currently, a regional power corporation supervises
both power plants and local grids.
</P>
<P>
Experts say this reform will be a significant step for the
monopoly power sector towards market competition, and help pave
the way for direct foreign investment in hydropower production.
</P>
<P>
China has exploitable hydropower potential of 378 million
kilowatts, the largest in the world. However, only 15 percent has
been exploited, compared with 50-90 percent in the West.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
