<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysts Clear Up Investment Confusion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 20 (Xinhua) -- observers confused by the
astounding investment plan announced earlier this month by a
senior Chinese official should check definitions of Chinese
economic terms, the "China Daily" quoted a veteran investment
researcher at the State Development Planning Commission as saying.
</P>
<P>
State Councillor Wu Yi said during a recent national trade fair
in Xiamen that China's investment volume during the 1998-2000
period would top 10 trillion yuan(1.2 trillion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The figure mystified many observers, who wondered how the
government could foot such a monumental bill.
</P>
<P>
"I think Wu was referring to fixed assets investment, which
covers not only investment from the government, but also from the
State firms and the non-State sector, which includes individuals
and foreign investors,"said Zhang Hanya, director of SDPC's
Investment Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used not only for infrastructure, because the
term "fixed assets investment" has a very broad definition which
also covers investment for plant construction, industrial
upgrading, and construction of State and private property, and
even investment for natural resources exploration, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
China's fixed assets investment totalled 2.53 trillion yuan
(304 billion US dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
The figure put forward by Wu indicates the country needs to
pursue a 15 percent annual growth rate in fixed assets investment
between 1998 and 2000 - a rate well above the original ten percent
proposed by the government for the period, but much smaller than
those registered during the first half of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Wu's announcement implied that the government will rely more on
fixed assets investment to sustain economic growth than it had
originally anticipated.
</P>
<P>
Although the government's input will account for a very small
fraction of the total investment, demand generated by
government-funded projects will prompt State companies and
non-State firms to launch new ventures and push the total
investment growth to the new projected volume, experts
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980920.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
