<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Honduran Army Placed Under Civilian Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The Honduran Congress
voted on Saturday to take away autonomy from the armed forces and
put them under civilian control.
</P>
<P>
The 128-seat National Assembly voted unanimously for a
constitutional revision proposed by Honduran President Carlos
Flores Facusse.
</P>
<P>
The Honduran armed forces had ruled the country for 41 years
until 1941, when under pressure from the United States, civilians
were allowed to run for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
But the army continued throwing their weight around. Civilian
presidents have been thwarted in their efforts to control the army
even when the army were charged with human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
Civilian courts were barred from trying army officer. The
situation started to change five years ago when the army agreed to
allow civilian courts to try their officers.
</P>
<P>
The constitutional revision also eliminated the authority of
the commander-in-chief, which had in the past overthrown a number
of presidents, either civilian or military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
