<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anhui Province To Build Billion-Yuan Reservoir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a reservoir on
a tributary of the Yangtze River which will cost more than one
billion yuan will soon begin in east China's Anhui Province, the
first water conservancy projects since the end of this year's vast
flooding.
</P>
<P>
Located in the city of Ningguo, the Gangkouwan reservoir will be
built on the Shuiyang River and will be one of the largest water
conservancy projects ever in the province.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir is expected to have 1,120 square kilometers of
drainage areas, and will have a storage capacity of 941 million
cubic meters of water, with normal water levels reaching 135
meters.
</P>
<P>
The project will submerge nearly 1,586 hectares of cultivated
land and require the resettlement of more than 18,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Since New China was founded in 1949, more than 20 major floods
have occurred in the Shuiyang River Valley, costing tens of
billions of yuan in economic losses.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir is expected to be completed in 2002, at which
time regional flooding will be completely controlled, 36,600
hectares of farmland will be protected, and 31,000 hectares of
farmland will be irrigated.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir will generate 113 million KWH of electricity
annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
