<HEADLINE> Kafelnikov to Play Henman in President's Cup Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TASHKENT, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Top two seeds Yevgeny
Kafelnikov of Russia and Tim Henman of Britain, overcame their
respective opponents on Saturday to set up the finals of the
500,000 U.S. dollars President's Cup tournament.
</P>
<P>
Second-seeded defending champion Henman eliminated
fourth-seeded Nicolas Escude of France 3-6, 6-3, 6-4, while top
seed Kafelnikov routed another Frenchman Cedric Pioline in
straight sets with an identical score of 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Henman, this year's Wimbledon semifinalist, said "it was my
best match this week."
</P>
<P>
"I met Kafelnikov six or seven times and only twice I won. He
is a very good player and it will be difficult to play him
tomorrow," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kafelnikov, 24, easily beat third-seeded Pioline for his ninth
victory in their 10 previous matches. Earlier this year he
outplayed Pioline in the finals for the Guardian Direct Cup
indoor title in west London.
</P>
<P>
"Pioline had a very tough game against Safin yesterday, which
lasted over two and a half hours. He came up tired for today's
game. That's why I won so confidently," said Kafelnikov.
</P>
<P>
Both players have a chance to earn a berth in the ATP
Championship in Hannover, Germany, this year, to join the ranks
of Marcelo Rios, Pete Sampras and Patrick Rafter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
